hands_on_practices.solution:
Let $I$ denote the event that the person is infected and $+$ denote a positive test result. By Bayes' theorem,
$$
P(I|+) = \frac{P(+|I)P(I)}{P(+|I)P(I) + P(+|\overline{I})P(\overline{I})}.
$$
Sensitivity is $P(+|I) = 0.99$, specificity is $P(-|\overline{I}) = 0.95$, so $P(+|\overline{I}) = 1 - 0.95 = 0.05$. The prevalence is $P(I) = 0.001$, hence $P(\overline{I}) = 1 - 0.001 = 0.999$. Substituting,
$$
P(I|+) = \frac{0.99 \cdot 0.001}{0.99 \cdot 0.001 + 0.05 \cdot 0.999}
= \frac{0.00099}{0.00099 + 0.04995}
= \frac{0.00099}{0.05094}
= \frac{99}{5094}
= \frac{11}{566}.
$$
Compute the decimal and round to three significant figures:
$$
\frac{11}{566} \approx 0.0194346 \quad \Rightarrow \quad 0.0194 \text{ (three significant figures).}
$$
